{
  "info": {
    "_postman_id": "bb43a0fb-1497-4067-ad99-01d8570107de",
    "name": "Budget Management Fault Tolerance",
    "description": "Demonstrates the MicroProfile Fault Tolerance annotations (Timeout and Circuit Breaker) that guard the two synchronous cross-service Rest Client calls (Deliverable C, section 7):\n\n- budget-service -> piggybank-service (GET /piggy-banks/totals), exercised through GET /api/v1/balance. @Timeout(2s) sits on PiggyBankClient.getTotals, @CircuitBreaker on BalanceService.getBalance.\n- piggybank-service -> identity-service (GET /users?email), exercised through POST /api/v1/invitations. @Timeout(2s) sits on IdentityClient.findByEmail, @CircuitBreaker on InvitationService.sendInvitation.\n\nEach downstream provider exposes a runtime-switchable fault simulator (PUT /api/v1/{piggybank|identity}/simulate/strategy) with three strategies: HEALTHY (no-op), SLOW (sleeps, drives the caller's Timeout), FAILING (throws 503, drives the caller's Circuit Breaker).\n\nThis collection is standalone: the '0) Setup' folder provisions its own user (faulttester@example.com) and group ('Fault Tolerance Demo'), both named so they do not collide with the 'Budget Management' collection (erika/ioannis/Flatmates). It can therefore run on the same cluster and databases after that collection without conflicts, and is safe to re-run (register tolerates 409, the group is looked up by name).\n\nThe circuit breaker is configured with requestVolumeThreshold=4, failureRatio=0.5 and a 3 second cool-down delay. Run with the Collection Runner using no (0 ms) delay between requests, so the OPEN-state checks land inside the 3 second cool-down window.\n\nSet {{baseUrl}} to the gateway URL (e.g. the output of 'minikube service gateway --url').",
    "schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json",
    "_exporter_id": "16408890"
  },
